&lt;h2 class="relative group">Ahamkaara vs Ego
&lt;div id="ahamkaara-vs-ego" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#ahamkaara-vs-ego" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>In my view, the distinction between &lt;strong>Ahamkaara&lt;/strong> and &lt;strong>Ego&lt;/strong> is subtle yet profound, especially when viewed from a philosophical and spiritual lens. Ahamkara is &lt;strong>a tool that can be refined&lt;/strong>, whereas ego is &lt;strong>an illusion that must be dissolved&lt;/strong>. If Ahamkara leads to the realization that &lt;strong>all is one&lt;/strong>, it becomes a stepping stone to enlightenment. But if it binds one to the material world, it becomes just another name for ego.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>